ce:section.ce:para:
Recently, J. Y. Park et al. designed a novel and sensitive aptasensor using MNPs with specific label-free DNA aptamers, and a colorimetric substrate tetramethylbenzidine (TMB) to handle the threat of poising with S. typhimurium 
                     [56]. The basic principle of this colorimetric biosensor is based on peroxidase-like activity of MNPs. Firstly DNA aptamers adsorbed MNPs through electrostatic interactions between the positively charged surface of the MNPs and the negatively charged of aptamers resulted blocking the surface of MNPs and reduces its enzyme-like activity. But in the presence of S. typhimurium in the solution mixed with MNPs and DNA aptamers, aptamer detached from the MNPs and the peroxidase activity of MNPs recovered causing a blue-colored product, which was detectable with naked eyes (Fig. 4
                     ). Detection limit of this biosensor is as low as 7.5 × 105 CFU/mL in buffer solution.
